---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import RelatedTools from '../../../components/RelatedTools.astro';

// Tool metadata
const name = "Key Repeat Test";
const category = "display";
const tier = "Display & Input Diagnostics";

// On-page SEO metadata
const pageTitle = "Key Repeat Test - Check Keyboard Repeat Rate & Delay Online";
const description = "Free online key repeat test to measure your keyboard's key repeat rate and key repeat delay. Check key repeat on Windows 11 & Mac, detect bouncy or ghost keys, and understand what key repeat rate means.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://toolkify.com/tools/display/key-repeat";
const ogImage = "/og/key-repeat.png";
const keywords = "key repeat test, what is key repeat rate, key repeat rate, key repeat, key repeat rate mac, key repeat delay, windows 11 key repeat rate, what does key repeat rate mean, key repeat vs delay until repeat, key repeat meaning, key repeat time, key repeat windows, key repeat test windows, what does key repeat mean";
---

<Layout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={description}
  toolName={name}
  toolCategory={category}
  keywords={keywords}
  canonical={canonicalUrl}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="website"
  hideBanner={true}
>
  <!-- SEO JSON-LD WebApplication Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "Keyboard Key Repeat Test",
      "alternateName": "Key Repeat Delay & Rate Analyzer",
      "url": "https://toolkify.com/tools/display/key-repeat",
      "description": "Measure physical keyboard repeat delay, auto-fire repeat rate, bounce double-presses, and stuck/ghost keys locally in your browser.",
      "applicationCategory": "DeveloperApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "All",
      "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires Physical Keyboard.",
      "featureList": [
        "OS-level repeat delay measurement in milliseconds",
        "Key-repeat rate frequency calculations (Hz)",
        "Hardware switch bounce (chatter) detection under custom threshold",
        "Ghost and stuck key hold duration flagging",
        "Individual per-key history and averages table",
        "Passive background monitoring free-typing text area",
        "CSV/JSON diagnostic log exporter",
        "100% private client-side processing"
      ],
      "offers": {
        "@type": "Offer",
        "price": "0.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD"
      }
    }
  </script>

  <!-- Breadcrumb Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      "itemListElement": [
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 1,
          "name": "Home",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 2,
          "name": "Tools",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 3,
          "name": "Display",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools/display"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 4,
          "name": "Key Repeat Test",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools/display/key-repeat"
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <!-- FAQ JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is key repeat rate?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Key repeat rate is the speed at which a single character is typed over and over when you press and hold a key on your keyboard. It is usually measured in characters per second (or hertz, Hz). A higher key repeat rate fires the held character more quickly, while a lower rate produces it more slowly. This key repeat test shows your live key repeat rate in Hz so you can see exactly how fast your keyboard auto-fires.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does key repeat rate mean?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Key repeat rate means how frequently your operating system re-sends the same keystroke while a key stays pressed down. Once the initial key repeat delay has passed, the system begins repeating the character at a steady interval, and that interval is the key repeat rate. In practical terms, a fast repeat rate lets you scroll, delete, or move a cursor rapidly by holding one key, whereas a slow rate makes those held-key actions feel sluggish.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is key repeat vs delay until repeat?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Delay until repeat (also called key repeat delay) is the pause between the moment you first press a key and the moment it starts repeating. Key repeat rate is how fast the character repeats after that pause ends. In short, the delay controls how long you must hold a key before it begins auto-firing, and the repeat rate controls how quickly it fires once it starts. Both settings work together, and this tool measures each of them separately in milliseconds and hertz.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the key repeat rate on Mac?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>On a Mac, the key repeat rate is adjusted under System Settings (or System Preferences) &rarr; Keyboard, using the &ldquo;Key Repeat&rdquo; and &ldquo;Delay Until Repeat&rdquo; sliders. macOS lets you set the repeat rate from slow up to fast, and power users can push it beyond the slider limits with a Terminal command. After changing the setting, run this key repeat test to confirm the new rate and delay are actually being applied by your Mac.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Samsung: what is key repeat time?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>On Samsung devices, key repeat time refers to how long a held key waits before it starts repeating and how quickly it repeats afterward. On a Samsung phone or tablet this applies to a connected physical keyboard, and on Samsung monitors or displays with built-in controls it can refer to how fast the menu buttons repeat when held. Because behavior varies by device, the most reliable check is to connect the keyboard and use this key repeat test to see the actual repeat time.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which function key repeat last command?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>In many Windows applications the F4 key repeats the last command &mdash; for example, in Microsoft Excel and Word, pressing F4 repeats your most recent action. In the classic Windows Command Prompt, F3 repeats the previous command line. These &ldquo;repeat last command&rdquo; shortcuts are separate from keyboard key repeat, which is the automatic character repetition you can measure with this key repeat test when holding any key down.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is key repeat time monitor?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A key repeat time monitor is a tool that watches your keystrokes in real time and reports the key repeat delay and key repeat rate as you hold keys down. This page is exactly that: it logs each keydown, keyup, and auto-repeat event, then displays your repeat delay in milliseconds, your repeat rate in hertz, and flags any bouncy or stuck keys. It runs entirely in your browser, so it monitors key repeat timing privately without sending any data to a server.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <section
