    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2
        id="about-tool-heading"
        class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight"
      >
        Free Online Key Repeat Test
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        This <strong>key repeat test</strong> is a fast, free, and completely
        private way to check exactly how your keyboard behaves when you press
        and hold a key. Every keyboard has two hidden timing values &mdash; the
        <strong>key repeat delay</strong> and the
        <strong>key repeat rate</strong> &mdash; and this tool measures both in
        real time, right in your browser. Just click the capture area, hold down
        any key such as Space, A, or an arrow key, and watch the live metrics
        update. Nothing you type is ever uploaded, because the entire key repeat
        test runs client-side on your own device.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If you have ever wondered <strong>what is key repeat rate</strong> or
        <strong>what does key repeat rate mean</strong>, the simplest answer is
        this: it is the speed at which a single character is fired over and over
        while a key stays pressed. So <strong>what does key repeat mean</strong>
        in everyday use? When you hold Backspace to erase a sentence or hold an
        arrow key to move the cursor, that automatic repetition is key repeat in
        action. This page turns those invisible values into clear numbers so you
        can understand and compare them across devices.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Key Repeat Rate vs Key Repeat Delay
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Understanding <strong>key repeat vs delay until repeat</strong> is the
        key to reading your results correctly. The
        <strong>key repeat delay</strong> is the pause between your first
        keypress and the moment the character starts repeating &mdash; it stops
        a quick tap from accidentally producing several letters. The
        <strong>key repeat rate</strong> is how quickly the character repeats
        once that delay is over. In other words, the delay decides
        <em>when</em> repetition begins and the rate decides <em>how fast</em>
        it goes. That is the full <strong>key repeat meaning</strong>: two
        timing values working together. This test reports the delay in
        milliseconds and the rate in hertz (Hz), and it also tracks each key's
        <strong>key repeat time</strong> individually so you can spot
        inconsistent switches.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Key Repeat on Windows
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        On Windows you can change your <strong>key repeat</strong> settings by
        opening Control Panel &rarr; Keyboard, where two sliders control the
        repeat delay and the repeat speed. If you are tuning the
        <strong>windows 11 key repeat rate</strong>, the same dialog is
        available by searching &ldquo;Keyboard&rdquo; in the Start menu. After
        adjusting <strong>key repeat windows</strong> settings, use this
        <strong>key repeat test windows</strong> users rely on to confirm the
        change actually took effect &mdash; hold a key and check whether the
        measured rate and delay match what you expect. It is the quickest way to
        verify Windows applied your new configuration.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Key Repeat Rate on Mac
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Mac users can adjust the <strong>key repeat rate mac</strong> setting
        under System Settings &rarr; Keyboard, using the &ldquo;Key
        Repeat&rdquo; and &ldquo;Delay Until Repeat&rdquo; sliders. macOS even
        allows advanced users to push the repeat rate faster than the slider
        limits with a Terminal command. Whichever method you use, this tool
        works identically on macOS, Windows, Linux, and ChromeOS, so you can run
        the same key repeat test after tweaking your Mac and immediately see the
        new timing values reflected on screen.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        More Than Just Repeat Timing
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Beyond measuring <strong>key repeat rate</strong> and
        <strong>key repeat delay</strong>, this diagnostic also flags two common
        hardware faults. It detects <strong>bouncy keys</strong> (chatter),
        where a worn switch registers two presses from a single tap within a few
        milliseconds, and it flags <strong>ghost or stuck keys</strong> that
        report as held far longer than physically plausible. A per-key summary
        table records the average repeat delay, average repeat rate, and a
        consistency rating for every key you test, and you can export the full
        keystroke log as CSV or JSON for deeper analysis or a warranty claim.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Why Use This Key Repeat Test
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Whether you are a gamer fine-tuning responsiveness, a writer bothered by
        a sluggish Backspace, or someone troubleshooting a suspected faulty
